<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 8:26<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I27da1d50630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>8.</label.designator><headtext>Relevancy</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id7201722682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>8:26.</label.designator><headtext>Offers to pay medical expenses</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Previously, Georgia courts held that an offer to pay the medical expenses of another was not an admission of liability if the offer was an expression of “benevolence or sympathy.”[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I797b810074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>] Now, under <cite.query w-src-number="0287017151" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-4-409" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="If3a9b10074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-4-409</cite.query>, <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“[e]vidence of furnishing, offering, or promising to pay medical, hospital, or similar expenses occasioned by an injury shall not be admissible to prove liability for the injury.”<eos/><end.quote refid="QT_0001"/></paratext><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="I797b810074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017151" w-serial-number="1995202515" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If3a8edb274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Neubert v. Vigh, 218 Ga. App. 693, 462 S.E.2d 808 (1995)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See also <cite.query w-src-number="0287017151" w-serial-number="1999059665" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If3a962e274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Widner v. Brookins, Inc., 236 Ga. App. 563, 565, 512 S.E.2d 405 (1999)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017151" w-serial-number="2011735921" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If3a962e574d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Petrosky v. Embry Crossing Condominium Ass&apos;n, Inc., 284 Ga. App. 354, 643 S.E.2d 855 (2007)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 8:26<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
